Good dogbriar.

00:26:30.560 --> 00:26:31.560
That's lovely.

00:26:31.560 --> 00:26:34.560
You know, I look at all these things.

00:26:34.560 --> 00:26:43.560
And now when my grandchildren, well, and my two, went into Newport to schools,

00:26:43.560 --> 00:26:47.560
because they took the boundary, took us in, just up the road,

00:26:47.560 --> 00:26:52.560
I didn't realise till my boy went to school.

00:26:52.560 --> 00:26:56.560
He is 53 this time and my girl's 49.

00:26:56.560 --> 00:26:58.560
Yeah, it is, I can't think.

00:26:58.560 --> 00:27:00.560
You forget, don't you?

00:27:00.560 --> 00:27:04.560
It's a different world.

00:27:04.560 --> 00:27:07.560
Completely different world.

00:27:07.560 --> 00:27:14.560
Because, how can I put it, they wasted too much.

00:27:14.560 --> 00:27:18.560
I used to love going to the jumble sales at the school

00:27:18.560 --> 00:27:23.560
because they'd throw out a skirt because the zip had gone.

00:27:23.560 --> 00:27:25.560
Beautiful clothes.

00:27:25.560 --> 00:27:29.560
And you get it for 10p.

00:27:29.560 --> 00:27:33.560
I'd come home, you know, only had to put a zip in.

00:27:33.560 --> 00:27:37.560
You know, but it was a completely different way of living.

00:27:37.560 --> 00:27:41.560
And I didn't realise that until they started school.

00:27:41.560 --> 00:27:44.560
Would you say yours was a very outdoor life?

00:27:44.560 --> 00:27:49.560
Yes, outdoor, but you didn't waste anything, get me?

00:27:49.560 --> 00:27:53.560
I mean, even to making cake and all that,

00:27:53.560 --> 00:27:58.560
you used a, what was there, I mean, if the cream went a little bit sour,

00:27:58.560 --> 00:28:04.560
you put it in a cake or in a scone, it'd make a lovely light scone.

00:28:04.560 --> 00:28:08.560
Not really gone off, you know, but just not tainted.

00:28:08.560 --> 00:28:12.560
I still use yogurts or whatever now.

00:28:12.560 --> 00:28:16.560
If a yogurt is out of date, as long as it hasn't blown, it goes in a cake.

00:28:16.560 --> 00:28:18.560
That's lovely.

00:28:18.560 --> 00:28:22.560
Where did your milk come from? Did you buy milk?

00:28:22.560 --> 00:28:25.560
No, we always had a house cow.

00:28:25.560 --> 00:28:30.560
Where the calf and Dad milked it or my brothers milked it,

00:28:30.560 --> 00:28:33.560
or I've had a milk sometimes, you know.

00:28:33.560 --> 00:28:37.560
If they weren't yearning, every morning the cow read the calf.

00:28:37.560 --> 00:28:41.560
But you had the milk first, you didn't let them run free.

00:28:41.560 --> 00:28:44.560
The calf was in the pen and you had your milk.

00:28:44.560 --> 00:28:47.560
Did you make butter and cheese?

00:28:47.560 --> 00:28:52.560
Yes, still got the churn, the old wooden churn and the glass churn is still here.

00:28:52.560 --> 00:28:55.560
Did you ever have to do that?

00:28:55.560 --> 00:28:58.560
So once you made the butter, where did you...?

00:28:58.560 --> 00:29:03.560
I got the pats and all, you were in it with, you know, you pat the...

00:29:03.560 --> 00:29:04.560
Yeah?

00:29:04.560 --> 00:29:05.560
Yeah.

00:29:05.560 --> 00:29:06.560
Gosh.

00:29:06.560 --> 00:29:08.560
Yeah, it's...

00:29:08.560 --> 00:29:12.560
This is what I think a lot of my grandchildren are losing out,

00:29:12.560 --> 00:29:17.560
because they think you buy everything out of a shop.

00:29:19.560 --> 00:29:20.560
I'm sorry.

00:29:20.560 --> 00:29:23.560
They're on the farm but they go to town schools.

00:29:23.560 --> 00:29:24.560
Yeah.

00:29:24.560 --> 00:29:26.560
What about pig? Did you have a family pig?

00:29:26.560 --> 00:29:29.560
Yes, yeah, we had a pig.

00:29:29.560 --> 00:29:33.560
And Dad used to kill a lamb, which he shared.

00:29:33.560 --> 00:29:38.560
There were three of them, Mr. Waters up the road and what you call over there.

00:29:38.560 --> 00:29:42.560
Well, he was another Mr. Waters, but he won a relation.

00:29:42.560 --> 00:29:43.560
It's strange.

00:29:43.560 --> 00:29:48.560
And my grandmother was a Waters, but she was relations to only one of them.

00:29:50.560 --> 00:29:54.560
We're all really on the moors mixed up with one another on the farm.

00:29:54.560 --> 00:29:57.560
I don't think they travel very far.

00:29:57.560 --> 00:30:01.560
What about... So you know you've got reams all around you.

00:30:01.560 --> 00:30:04.560
From an early age were you told to keep away from them?

00:30:04.560 --> 00:30:05.560
Yes.

00:30:05.560 --> 00:30:07.560
What did your parents say?

00:30:07.560 --> 00:30:15.560
They'd tell us never play near a ream, because if you fall in you might not get out.

00:30:15.560 --> 00:30:19.560
Because some of the reams have got a base around you.

00:30:19.560 --> 00:30:23.560
They're not all clay. Well, people suck you down.

00:30:23.560 --> 00:30:27.560
And you were never to play near a ream.

00:30:27.560 --> 00:30:31.560
Never to talk to strangers, but I never seen any strangers.

00:30:31.560 --> 00:30:32.560
Oh, yeah.

00:30:32.560 --> 00:30:35.560
Because you knew everybody.

00:30:35.560 --> 00:30:39.560
And Dad used to cut people's hair.

00:30:39.560 --> 00:30:42.560
And he'd come in and say, oh, yes, he'd trim the...

00:30:42.560 --> 00:30:45.560
I still got his cutters in the old drawer outside.

00:30:45.560 --> 00:30:50.560
Really, Cuff? So people would come to your kitchen and he would cut their hair?

00:30:50.560 --> 00:30:51.560
Yeah.

00:30:51.560 --> 00:30:53.560
What, quite regularly?

00:30:53.560 --> 00:30:54.560
Yeah.

00:30:56.560 --> 00:30:58.560
I'll always remember.

00:30:58.560 --> 00:30:59.560
Just men or women's?

00:30:59.560 --> 00:31:02.560
Oh, Dad done women too. He used to cut mine.

00:31:02.560 --> 00:31:08.560
But he did do the next door neighbors and a couple, you know, they'd come and he'd do it.

00:31:08.560 --> 00:31:13.560
Never had no training, but he'd cut the hair, the hand clippers and all that.

00:31:13.560 --> 00:31:20.560
And it's ever so funny because on a Sunday morning, this man used to come to dinner every Sunday.

00:31:20.560 --> 00:31:24.560
I didn't know who he was, because you had to be...

00:31:24.560 --> 00:31:27.560
I was being about six then, I expect.

00:31:27.560 --> 00:31:29.560
Seen but not heard?

00:31:29.560 --> 00:31:34.560
Yeah. So you didn't ask questions, but they didn't talk a lot then, did they?

00:31:34.560 --> 00:31:37.560
Our mother didn't seem to talk a lot.

00:31:37.560 --> 00:31:44.560
And he'd be here every Sunday to dinner and I'd think, oh.

00:31:44.560 --> 00:31:48.560
Then Mum said to him, now that's your Uncle Morgan.

00:31:48.560 --> 00:31:55.560
Well, I had an auntie Claire up the road, no relation, and Auntie Annis and all those, no relations with her.

00:31:55.560 --> 00:31:59.560
And Uncle Morgan, asked me, Uncle Morgan.

00:31:59.560 --> 00:32:02.560
Why wonder where does he live?

00:32:02.560 --> 00:32:08.560
Well, every Sunday he was at dinner with our mam.

00:32:08.560 --> 00:32:11.560
It turned out he was our mam's brother.

00:32:11.560 --> 00:32:12.560
Really?

00:32:12.560 --> 00:32:17.560
Yeah. He said, you're coming home with me today?

00:32:17.560 --> 00:32:20.560
Am I?

00:32:20.560 --> 00:32:24.560
Yeah, you can go. You can go, because Auntie Anna wants to see you.

00:32:24.560 --> 00:32:29.560
Oh. Well, we peddled all up the moor.

00:32:29.560 --> 00:32:34.560
He lived at Land of Any, right by the railway line, where the bridge goes off.

00:32:34.560 --> 00:32:39.560
Was it Whitehall, the farm right by the railway line?

00:32:39.560 --> 00:32:42.560
Well, he lived right by there.

00:32:42.560 --> 00:32:48.560
Well, we'd go and sit in the house, but he had eight children.

00:32:48.560 --> 00:32:50.560
Wow.

00:32:50.560 --> 00:32:55.560
I stayed there. I wonder why mam had packed my...

00:32:58.560 --> 00:33:03.560
It was then when I found out he was mam's brother.

00:33:03.560 --> 00:33:07.560
Because mamma never told me, should you go in and stay up there? So that was my holiday then.

00:33:07.560 --> 00:33:10.560
It was your holiday, how funny.

00:33:10.560 --> 00:33:14.560
Yeah. And I had a couple of days up there.

00:33:14.560 --> 00:33:21.560
And then we peddled up like that. Well, he'd already told me that I was their cousin, and you know.

00:33:21.560 --> 00:33:25.560
We slept three in a bed.

00:33:25.560 --> 00:33:29.560
Two on that end, one at the other end, you know.

00:33:29.560 --> 00:33:31.560
The girls and me.

00:33:31.560 --> 00:33:34.560
Had you peddled everywhere in those days, Michael?

00:33:34.560 --> 00:33:43.560
Yeah. But what I couldn't cope with, because the house was so near the railway line, and we are so quiet here,

00:33:43.560 --> 00:33:47.560
oh, those blooming trains, they'd rattle by.

00:33:47.560 --> 00:33:49.560
Would they be the steam train then?

00:33:49.560 --> 00:33:54.560
Yeah, but they'd be going quite fast, and they'd carry on talking.

00:33:54.560 --> 00:34:05.560
But I couldn't hear a thing. They must have got oblivious to the noise, and they'd be talking away, and I couldn't hear a thing.

00:34:05.560 --> 00:34:09.560
And in bed at night, there weren't many at night, mind.

00:34:09.560 --> 00:34:18.560
I suppose today there's trains all the time, but you go to bed and you hear, oh, this blooming train, you hear it coming down the line, you know.

00:34:18.560 --> 00:34:27.560
And it'd be more or less the house was only like from here to that wall over there from the actual train.

00:34:27.560 --> 00:34:34.560
But that man that came in every Sunday was Mums Weather.

00:34:34.560 --> 00:34:38.560
So as a child, what sort of games did you play?

00:34:38.560 --> 00:34:47.560
Opscotch, skipping, climbing trees, falling out many a time.

00:34:47.560 --> 00:34:50.560
Did you ever swim in the reams despite being a cockatoo?

00:34:50.560 --> 00:34:51.560
No.

00:34:51.560 --> 00:34:54.560
No boating or jumping over them?

00:34:54.560 --> 00:34:59.560
No, except that day when my two brothers trod on my hands going over.

00:34:59.560 --> 00:35:02.560
What about the sea wall? Did you ever go down there?

00:35:02.560 --> 00:35:09.560
No, that was the walk from school, our nature walk from school.

00:35:09.560 --> 00:35:10.560
Yeah.

00:35:10.560 --> 00:35:14.560
Because you never went like they do abroad and all they do today.

00:35:14.560 --> 00:35:21.560
You either went down a lane, you went up the sea wall, or you took nature walks.

00:35:21.560 --> 00:35:24.560
So what did you do on the sea wall?

00:35:24.560 --> 00:35:26.560
There's a little bit of sand on the one side.

00:35:26.560 --> 00:35:30.560
You'd walk in, the fisheries used to be there, they used to catch the fish, look.

00:35:30.560 --> 00:35:31.560
Yeah.

00:35:31.560 --> 00:35:35.560
And then you'd walk in there and play on this little bit of sand.

00:35:35.560 --> 00:35:41.560
And there was always tea rooms down there because there used to be a big house called the Temporous Hotel.

00:35:41.560 --> 00:35:44.560
A three-storey house at the sea wall, they took it down.

00:35:44.560 --> 00:35:45.560
Where was that?

00:35:45.560 --> 00:35:51.560
Right as you drive down to the, go down the sea, right to the sea wall as far as you can go.

00:35:51.560 --> 00:35:53.560
You don't mean Porton?

00:35:53.560 --> 00:35:54.560
No, no.

00:35:54.560 --> 00:35:56.560
The actual Clifton Court one.

00:35:56.560 --> 00:35:58.560
Oh, the little cafe there?

00:35:58.560 --> 00:35:59.560
Yeah.

00:35:59.560 --> 00:36:03.560
Well, the cafe used to be in the house before that.

00:36:03.560 --> 00:36:04.560
Yeah.

00:36:04.560 --> 00:36:05.560
When I was a kid.

00:36:05.560 --> 00:36:06.560
Yeah.

00:36:06.560 --> 00:36:10.560
But there was a house the other side right on the sea wall, Temporous Hotel it was called.

00:36:10.560 --> 00:36:12.560
I've not heard of that before.

00:36:12.560 --> 00:36:13.560
Yeah, I remember Temporous.

00:36:13.560 --> 00:36:15.560
Yeah, three-storey house.

00:36:15.560 --> 00:36:19.560
Newtons lived in it, Mr. and Mrs. Newton, Bill Newton lived in it.

00:36:19.560 --> 00:36:20.560
Really?

00:36:20.560 --> 00:36:23.560
And there's another story.

00:36:23.560 --> 00:36:29.560
If you go over the New Southern Bridge and you come to England, as you look on the left,

00:36:29.560 --> 00:36:32.560
there's a house there, three-storey, exactly the same as the one that used to be down there.

00:36:32.560 --> 00:36:33.560
They took it down.

00:36:33.560 --> 00:36:34.560
Down there.

00:36:34.560 --> 00:36:35.560
Really?

00:36:35.560 --> 00:36:36.560
Yeah, you'll see it on the left-hand side.

00:36:36.560 --> 00:36:40.560
They took it down because they wanted to do something to the sea wall and they moved it.

00:36:40.560 --> 00:36:42.560
Yeah, when they widened the wall, yeah.

00:36:42.560 --> 00:36:44.560
Wait a minute.

00:36:44.560 --> 00:36:45.560
70s?

00:36:45.560 --> 00:36:47.560
70-something?

00:36:47.560 --> 00:36:48.560
Yes.

00:36:48.560 --> 00:36:52.560
Well, she was still living in the whole house when her son got lost on the Southern Bridge.

00:36:52.560 --> 00:36:53.560
70-something?

00:36:53.560 --> 00:36:54.560
What, he got lost in 60-something?

00:36:54.560 --> 00:36:55.560
He got lost?

00:36:55.560 --> 00:36:56.560
What do you mean?

00:36:56.560 --> 00:37:03.560
Well, he was working on the Southern Bridge and he was getting in his car on the... he'd

00:37:03.560 --> 00:37:04.560
finished his shift.

00:37:04.560 --> 00:37:05.560
Yeah.

00:37:05.560 --> 00:37:09.560
And an alarm went off and he rushed back in and he got in the boats and he never ever found

00:37:09.560 --> 00:37:10.560
his body.

00:37:10.560 --> 00:37:13.560
They reckoned he'd got under one of the other boats or something.

00:37:13.560 --> 00:37:15.560
There's a thing about it on the telly.

00:37:15.560 --> 00:37:17.560
Oh yeah, there was a program on it about telly.

00:37:17.560 --> 00:37:18.560
Really?

00:37:18.560 --> 00:37:21.560
It was the only funeral I remember my dad going to.

00:37:21.560 --> 00:37:22.560
Oh, sorry.

00:37:22.560 --> 00:37:26.560
No, my brother's going to where there was no body.

00:37:26.560 --> 00:37:32.560
Mam's sister lived the other way on the sea wall then.

00:37:32.560 --> 00:37:33.560
Yeah.

00:37:33.560 --> 00:37:41.560
But when she was ill, she'd give me two and sixpence anti-D.E.C. did to go and do her ironing.

00:37:41.560 --> 00:37:47.560
So I used to ride down to Mrs. Newton's and walk the sea wall all the way down there to

00:37:47.560 --> 00:37:49.560
do her ironing and come back.

00:37:49.560 --> 00:37:54.560
Two and sixpence if she had a lot of ironing, two shillings if it was a small iron.

00:37:54.560 --> 00:37:56.560
So, it depended on...

00:37:56.560 --> 00:37:59.560
How far along the sea wall did you...

00:37:59.560 --> 00:38:01.560
Oh, Grimineck, Mildermore.

00:38:01.560 --> 00:38:02.560
Really?

00:38:02.560 --> 00:38:06.560
You walked, yeah, to there, come back, pedal my back home.

00:38:06.560 --> 00:38:10.560
So the Temperance Hotel, was it a hotel?

00:38:10.560 --> 00:38:11.560
People would go there...

00:38:11.560 --> 00:38:14.560
At one stage, but not when Newton's was there.

00:38:14.560 --> 00:38:15.560
Yeah.

00:38:15.560 --> 00:38:22.560
Mrs. Newton, who used to wait, I used to put my bike in her coal house in her shed on the

00:38:22.560 --> 00:38:27.560
side, and she'd wait until I'd come back, see me walk back along the sea wall and have

00:38:27.560 --> 00:38:30.560
a few words with me and I'd pedal home then.

00:38:30.560 --> 00:38:31.560
Really?

00:38:31.560 --> 00:38:32.560
But you knew everybody, see?

00:38:32.560 --> 00:38:33.560
Yeah.

00:38:33.560 --> 00:38:35.560
And Mam used to go there.

00:38:35.560 --> 00:38:41.560
Well then, Auntie Daisy moved from there then, and she moved where Margaret Russell used

00:38:41.560 --> 00:38:44.560
to live on the Cardcliffe and Court.

00:38:44.560 --> 00:38:45.560
Oh, really?

00:38:45.560 --> 00:38:46.560
Um...

00:38:48.560 --> 00:38:49.560
She moved there.

00:38:49.560 --> 00:38:54.560
Did you ever go out into the estuary and walk out there or swim in the river there?

00:38:54.560 --> 00:38:58.560
No, we used to walk out, but I tell you what, we used to go more than anywhere.

00:38:58.560 --> 00:38:59.560
It was down...

00:39:01.560 --> 00:39:03.560
Oh, not Saltmash, there was a lot of grass.

00:39:03.560 --> 00:39:04.560
Yeah.

00:39:05.560 --> 00:39:07.560
Oh, what's that lane where you go to Nash Church?

00:39:07.560 --> 00:39:08.560
Walk on down there.

00:39:08.560 --> 00:39:10.560
Oh, I know where you go, yeah.

00:39:10.560 --> 00:39:15.560
And down there, there was a lot of grass.

00:39:15.560 --> 00:39:16.560
Yeah.

00:39:16.560 --> 00:39:20.560
And it was lovely to go and you could watch the ships come in through the dock down there,

00:39:20.560 --> 00:39:21.560
look.

00:39:21.560 --> 00:39:22.560
Oh, really?

00:39:22.560 --> 00:39:24.560
You'd be watching the ships coming into the dock.

00:39:24.560 --> 00:39:25.560
Yeah.

00:39:25.560 --> 00:39:30.560
And then we used to have a ride sometimes on our bikes, because you never took shopping

00:39:30.560 --> 00:39:33.560
with your mam in those days, right?

00:39:33.560 --> 00:39:40.560
And to see the shops when I was about 13, we used to go over the transporter bridge,

00:39:40.560 --> 00:39:43.560
pedal our bikes up the main street of town.

00:39:43.560 --> 00:39:45.560
Pedal your bikes to Newport?

00:39:45.560 --> 00:39:51.560
Yeah, we'd pedal our bikes down where the transporter bridge is in Traston Road.

00:39:51.560 --> 00:39:53.560
And you went across on the transporter bridge?

00:39:53.560 --> 00:39:56.560
Up where the cross on the transporter bridge.

00:39:56.560 --> 00:40:01.560
Pedal our bikes up town, looking in the shop windows, right?

00:40:01.560 --> 00:40:02.560
Yeah.

00:40:02.560 --> 00:40:08.560
And then come on along down Chepstral Road, turn off at the crosshands and pedal on.

00:40:08.560 --> 00:40:11.560
And that was not everything, it was only in the summer.

00:40:11.560 --> 00:40:14.560
You'd see lovely shoes, you'd see everything, you know.

00:40:14.560 --> 00:40:18.560
But you had to have plain Jane when you went to school, didn't you?

00:40:18.560 --> 00:40:20.560
Oh my God, that's such a lovely story.

00:40:20.560 --> 00:40:26.560
We used to have fun as kids, I mean, we had no money.

00:40:26.560 --> 00:40:28.560
No money, no?

00:40:28.560 --> 00:40:30.560
Were there any shops in the parish?

00:40:30.560 --> 00:40:33.560
Yes, sure, shop on the end of Straits Lane.

00:40:33.560 --> 00:40:43.560
And there was one down by Eskmouth, it was a post office, Thomas's, Moorcroft.

00:40:43.560 --> 00:40:54.560
And there was one in Whitsun, yeah, she used to do post office and pension, she didn't have a shop.

00:40:54.560 --> 00:40:56.560
She just had the actual pensions.

00:40:56.560 --> 00:41:00.560
And the post got delivered and the post lady had pedaled around with mail.

00:41:00.560 --> 00:41:01.560
Really?

00:41:01.560 --> 00:41:05.560
Yeah, get delivered there, I mean, they'd pedaled around with the mail.

00:41:05.560 --> 00:41:10.560
Our mail used to come from Lamburn, yeah, they'd come over the railway line.

00:41:10.560 --> 00:41:11.560
Really?

00:41:11.560 --> 00:41:17.560
Yeah, there was a railway line there, look, you could go up there, pedal over and get over into Langston if you wanted to.

00:41:17.560 --> 00:41:22.560
Do you remember the butcher ranks out there at Porton?

00:41:22.560 --> 00:41:23.560
Yes.

00:41:23.560 --> 00:41:24.560
Yes?

00:41:24.560 --> 00:41:26.560
Yes, yes, I remember all those.

00:41:26.560 --> 00:41:29.560
My cousin used to fetch the salmon in.

00:41:29.560 --> 00:41:30.560
Who's your cousin?

00:41:30.560 --> 00:41:32.560
Baker, oh he's been dead years now.

00:41:32.560 --> 00:41:37.560
That was Auntie Daisy, used to go and do the ironing is, right there, yeah.

00:41:37.560 --> 00:41:49.560
And I tell you who used to do it here at the seawall down here, it all belonged to the same fishing, Burgess I think used, and then Williams's, it was Burgess.

00:41:49.560 --> 00:41:50.560
Yeah, I've heard the name Burgess.

00:41:50.560 --> 00:41:54.560
And then I think Williams's bought it after he died.

00:41:54.560 --> 00:41:58.560
Yes, because they had, he's still living down there, one of the Williams's.

00:41:58.560 --> 00:42:00.560
Really, yeah, Adrian Williams.

00:42:00.560 --> 00:42:02.560
That's it, yes, he's living down there.

00:42:02.560 --> 00:42:03.560
Yeah.

00:42:03.560 --> 00:42:10.560
I've seen him for years, and then Martin Hazel lives in Hill Farm, on the top.

00:42:10.560 --> 00:42:15.560
Hazel's origin, his father and my, his mother and my father are first cousins.

00:42:15.560 --> 00:42:16.560
Oh really?

00:42:16.560 --> 00:42:18.560
Yeah, I told you they didn't go very far did they?

00:42:18.560 --> 00:42:19.560
No.

00:42:19.560 --> 00:42:20.560
She was a hale.

00:42:20.560 --> 00:42:23.560
So your cousin used to fetch the salmon?

00:42:23.560 --> 00:42:36.560
Yeah, well he used to go out with a little tractor to fetch it in, and in the house there where he lived, down Auntie Daisy, right by there, they had slabs, called slabs.

00:42:36.560 --> 00:42:37.560
Yeah.

00:42:37.560 --> 00:42:45.560
And they'd put the, he'd go and get them out of the pouches and then put them in his place for them to come and collect.

00:42:45.560 --> 00:42:46.560
Oh my goodness.

00:42:46.560 --> 00:42:50.560
The salmon, see the salmon there, they look nice too.

00:42:50.560 --> 00:42:51.560
So was this at Goldcliff?

00:42:51.560 --> 00:42:52.560
That was at Goldcliff.

00:42:52.560 --> 00:42:53.560
Yeah.

00:42:53.560 --> 00:43:00.560
Well then what you call owls used to do it at, by Hazel's, then by Williams's.

00:43:00.560 --> 00:43:04.560
What you call, not Tudor owls.

00:43:04.560 --> 00:43:05.560
Windham.

00:43:05.560 --> 00:43:06.560
Windham owls.

00:43:06.560 --> 00:43:07.560
Did you know him?

00:43:07.560 --> 00:43:08.560
Yes.

00:43:08.560 --> 00:43:09.560
Really?

00:43:09.560 --> 00:43:13.560
Yes, yeah he was lovely, he knew us all, he did.

00:43:13.560 --> 00:43:16.560
What was he like, because I got some photographs of him.

00:43:16.560 --> 00:43:17.560
Yeah.

00:43:17.560 --> 00:43:18.560
Erm.

00:43:18.560 --> 00:43:20.560
Is that all he did, was he just a fisherman?

00:43:20.560 --> 00:43:26.560
Yeah, yeah, yeah, Windham yeah, father than that.

00:43:26.560 --> 00:43:29.560
Did you ever get fish from there, or did you ever fish?

00:43:29.560 --> 00:43:30.560
No, no.

00:43:30.560 --> 00:43:39.560
The only fishing I ever done was, well we lost it all now when the steel has come.

00:43:39.560 --> 00:43:41.560
My father used to like eels.

00:43:41.560 --> 00:43:42.560
Yes.

00:43:42.560 --> 00:43:48.560
So the bean sticks that he used to get, the stick for the runner beans, you'd add a bit

00:43:48.560 --> 00:43:54.560
of wire on it and a nook, stick it in the bank and then go back at night to see if you caught

00:43:54.560 --> 00:43:55.560
any in the rain.

00:43:55.560 --> 00:43:56.560
Yeah.

00:43:56.560 --> 00:43:58.560
Oh yeah, I used to catch them like fun.

00:43:58.560 --> 00:43:59.560
Really?

00:43:59.560 --> 00:44:04.560
Yeah, and I tell you what we used to see, and I don't know whether they're there now,

00:44:04.560 --> 00:44:09.560
down the bottom of Chappel Ream before it goes out to sea, right, you'd see bunches

00:44:09.560 --> 00:44:11.560
of eels, you know they.

00:44:11.560 --> 00:44:12.560
Elvers.

00:44:12.560 --> 00:44:15.560
Elvers, yeah, they'd be there in bunches.

00:44:15.560 --> 00:44:17.560
Yes, I've heard this.

00:44:17.560 --> 00:44:18.560
Yeah.

00:44:18.560 --> 00:44:19.560
But you could see them.

00:44:19.560 --> 00:44:20.560
Oh yeah, they were like.

00:44:20.560 --> 00:44:21.560
Like big club flat.

00:44:21.560 --> 00:44:22.560
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:44:22.560 --> 00:44:23.560
Really?

00:44:23.560 --> 00:44:24.560
Yeah, oh aye.

00:44:24.560 --> 00:44:26.560
So you used to go and watch that?

00:44:26.560 --> 00:44:27.560
Yeah.

00:44:27.560 --> 00:44:31.560
Well the thing is, what else was there to watch around you?

00:44:31.560 --> 00:44:35.560
Did anyone ever eat Elvers here?

00:44:35.560 --> 00:44:38.560
Not the Elvers, but Dad liked the eels.

00:44:38.560 --> 00:44:41.560
So when he caught the eel, did he bring it back?

00:44:41.560 --> 00:44:44.560
I'd go down and look and fetch it back, Rod as well.

00:44:44.560 --> 00:44:46.560
You'd fetch it back?

00:44:46.560 --> 00:44:49.560
Rod as well, only on the end of our road.

00:44:49.560 --> 00:44:50.560
Yeah?

00:44:50.560 --> 00:44:51.560
Yeah.

00:44:51.560 --> 00:44:52.560
How many would you have, just the one?

00:44:52.560 --> 00:44:58.560
Well if you took three bean sticks down with you and he'd come and show you how to push

00:44:58.560 --> 00:45:03.560
it in the bank, well then you didn't go back till about two or three hours, and you could

00:45:03.560 --> 00:45:04.560
have three.

00:45:04.560 --> 00:45:08.560
And he used to love them, Mam used to boil them for him.

00:45:08.560 --> 00:45:10.560
So did she skin them first?

00:45:10.560 --> 00:45:11.560
Yeah.

00:45:11.560 --> 00:45:16.560
She'd have an old sink outside where she'd put them in.

00:45:16.560 --> 00:45:18.560
Oh, and she boiled them?

00:45:18.560 --> 00:45:19.560
Mm-mm.

00:45:19.560 --> 00:45:22.560
Don't ask me how she'd done it, but she boiled them.

00:45:22.560 --> 00:45:26.560
So did that stop when landlorn went up?

00:45:26.560 --> 00:45:33.560
It went, well yes you got dirt would come in the water, which he said they wouldn't

00:45:33.560 --> 00:45:35.560
pollute, but they did.

00:45:35.560 --> 00:45:39.560
And you could go out sometimes and they'd have something burst over there.

00:45:39.560 --> 00:45:44.560
Oh, I mean, did they have arsenic or cyanide over there?

00:45:44.560 --> 00:45:47.560
And all the fish would be up on top of the water dead.

00:45:47.560 --> 00:45:48.560
You actually saw that?

00:45:48.560 --> 00:45:49.560
Really?

00:45:49.560 --> 00:45:50.560
Yeah.

00:45:50.560 --> 00:45:56.560
And that was in Monks Pill, and, because like Monks Pill joins us down here look, just down

00:45:56.560 --> 00:45:57.560
the road.

00:45:57.560 --> 00:45:58.560
Yeah.

00:45:58.560 --> 00:46:01.560
And, yeah, they'd be floating on top of the water.

00:46:01.560 --> 00:46:05.560
They'd had a leak, didn't they, or something over there, and nobody's seen anything would

00:46:05.560 --> 00:46:06.560
they?

00:46:06.560 --> 00:46:08.560
Do you remember when landlorn was being constructed?

00:46:08.560 --> 00:46:09.560
Yeah.

00:46:09.560 --> 00:46:11.560
What was that like?

00:46:11.560 --> 00:46:18.560
Terrible for us along here, because the lorries, which was all in the shale and all that, you'd

00:46:18.560 --> 00:46:23.560
see, well it wasn't safe to go out on the roads really, because they'd be coming up

00:46:23.560 --> 00:46:24.560
fast.

00:46:24.560 --> 00:46:29.560
They'd be in hedges, they'd be everywhere.

00:46:29.560 --> 00:46:34.560
You'd see a lorry, they did, you'd see, you know, they were everywhere.

00:46:34.560 --> 00:46:38.560
And you didn't want to go into the main of Newport, because there was only one bridge

00:46:38.560 --> 00:46:40.560
then, look, which was the old bridge.

00:46:40.560 --> 00:46:41.560
Oh my gosh.

00:46:41.560 --> 00:46:45.560
Not the George Street Bridge, and we've got City Bridge now.

00:46:45.560 --> 00:46:52.560
So you could be queuing way down on Corporation Road, or Chepster Road, because the lorries

00:46:52.560 --> 00:46:54.560
took over.

00:46:54.560 --> 00:46:59.560
And then you had to camp up the road, yeah, with all the Irishmen.

00:46:59.560 --> 00:47:00.560
Really?

00:47:00.560 --> 00:47:01.560
Yeah.

00:47:01.560 --> 00:47:07.560
You know where NRW is now, well, Caldercott and Wendtl was, but just up the road there,

00:47:07.560 --> 00:47:10.560
coming towards me on the left-hand side, there was an hostel there.

00:47:10.560 --> 00:47:15.560
There was even a church they put in there for the Irishmen, they were all Irish.

00:47:15.560 --> 00:47:16.560
Really?

00:47:16.560 --> 00:47:17.560
Mm-hmm.

00:47:17.560 --> 00:47:22.560
They were there building, they were the main ones on the stewardess, and they'd go to

00:47:22.560 --> 00:47:32.560
a town on a Friday night, come home drunk, and the old, no, I don't call them, a priest

00:47:32.560 --> 00:47:36.560
would be collecting them up, because there used to be a garage there selling petrol where

00:47:36.560 --> 00:47:39.560
NRW is now, German's Garage.

00:47:39.560 --> 00:47:40.560
Really?

00:47:40.560 --> 00:47:46.560
When we had a car then, we picked our petrol up there, and he used to shoe horses as well

00:47:46.560 --> 00:47:47.560
for anybody to ride.

00:47:47.560 --> 00:47:54.560
He had his thing in the back, Mr. German did, where he showed the horses, and he had two

00:47:54.560 --> 00:47:55.560
petrol pumps there.

00:47:55.560 --> 00:47:56.560
Wow.

00:47:56.560 --> 00:47:58.560
And behind that was the hostel.

00:47:58.560 --> 00:48:02.560
Just, you know where Geoff said he was born, that farm opposite?

00:48:02.560 --> 00:48:03.560
Oh, yeah, yeah.

00:48:03.560 --> 00:48:08.560
And that side of the road, just around the bend, you'll see like a lot of rubble now.

00:48:08.560 --> 00:48:09.560
Yeah.

00:48:09.560 --> 00:48:11.560
And that was the hostel where the Irishmen was.

00:48:11.560 --> 00:48:14.560
And they had a little church there as well?

00:48:14.560 --> 00:48:20.560
Yeah, and they used to go to town, get drunk, and oh, it was, you never come along that

00:48:20.560 --> 00:48:23.560
road on a Saturday night because they'd be all over the road.

00:48:23.560 --> 00:48:24.560
Oh.

00:48:24.560 --> 00:48:28.560
And the priest would be rounding them up and taking them in.

00:48:28.560 --> 00:48:30.560
I've not heard that before.

00:48:30.560 --> 00:48:31.560
Yes.

00:48:31.560 --> 00:48:32.560
Where?

00:48:32.560 --> 00:48:38.560
Up on that road, near a new port, there was a caravan site for the workers on the steelworks.

00:48:38.560 --> 00:48:39.560
Really?

00:48:39.560 --> 00:48:40.560
Yeah.

00:48:40.560 --> 00:48:46.560
And they had a church up on there as well, and a supermarket, like not today, like a

00:48:46.560 --> 00:48:47.560
corp on there.

00:48:47.560 --> 00:48:48.560
Yeah.

00:48:48.560 --> 00:48:50.560
I used to go in and get stuff, and a post office and all that.

00:48:50.560 --> 00:48:51.560
Oh my goodness.

00:48:51.560 --> 00:48:55.560
That must have been, do you remember the village of Lambwine?

00:48:55.560 --> 00:48:56.560
Yes.

00:48:56.560 --> 00:48:57.560
What was it like?

00:48:57.560 --> 00:49:00.560
Well, by the, do you know where the golf club is?

00:49:00.560 --> 00:49:01.560
Yeah.

00:49:01.560 --> 00:49:04.560
Well, that Tennyson Avenue, was it?

00:49:04.560 --> 00:49:08.560
Or Tennyson Road, I think, because we used to pedal our bikes over the railway.

00:49:08.560 --> 00:49:09.560
Did you?

00:49:09.560 --> 00:49:13.560
And then go up around the Martin and come back home along the moor.

00:49:13.560 --> 00:49:16.560
Well, there was nowhere else to go, you know.

00:49:16.560 --> 00:49:17.560
Yes.

00:49:17.560 --> 00:49:20.560
And then there was Banffam.

00:49:20.560 --> 00:49:24.560
We used to turn up by there, but like the little village was there by the Milton and

00:49:24.560 --> 00:49:27.560
all that, and few around by there.

00:49:27.560 --> 00:49:30.560
Do you know anyone who worked there at Lambwine?

00:49:30.560 --> 00:49:33.560
Did it employ a lot of local people?

00:49:33.560 --> 00:49:34.560
Yes.

00:49:34.560 --> 00:49:40.560
I mean, a lot of people from around here worked when the work started, you know.

00:49:40.560 --> 00:49:43.560
But it was mainly the Irish that was...

00:49:43.560 --> 00:49:46.560
That Irish Navvies that were building it.

00:49:46.560 --> 00:49:47.560
Yeah.

00:49:47.560 --> 00:49:48.560
Yeah.

00:49:48.560 --> 00:49:49.560
Oh my gosh.

00:49:49.560 --> 00:49:52.560
What about, so you were born in 41?

00:49:52.560 --> 00:49:53.560
41, January.

00:49:53.560 --> 00:49:56.560
Do you remember the winter of 47?

00:49:56.560 --> 00:49:57.560
Yes.

00:49:57.560 --> 00:50:03.560
Yes, where the sheep, we had snow, a bad winter, and you'd go out in the field out there and

00:50:03.560 --> 00:50:07.560
all you'd see was the poor sheep and their nostrils showing.

00:50:07.560 --> 00:50:13.560
And Dad used to, and Uncle and my two brothers, not me, because I mean, the snow was...

00:50:13.560 --> 00:50:14.560
Yeah.

00:50:14.560 --> 00:50:15.560
Oh, I remember that well.

00:50:15.560 --> 00:50:16.560
Wow.

00:50:16.560 --> 00:50:17.560
Was it cut off here then?

00:50:17.560 --> 00:50:18.560
Yeah.

00:50:18.560 --> 00:50:20.560
Yes, we were cut off.

00:50:20.560 --> 00:50:21.560
Gosh.

00:50:21.560 --> 00:50:24.560
And was it the same in 63?

00:50:24.560 --> 00:50:25.560
That's another bad winter.

00:50:25.560 --> 00:50:27.560
That was another one, yes.

00:50:27.560 --> 00:50:32.560
We could get from here with a tractor then, because you had tractors then, you know.

00:50:32.560 --> 00:50:34.560
So you got from here.

00:50:34.560 --> 00:50:39.560
I mean, you didn't go out there, you went and did any shopping.

00:50:39.560 --> 00:50:40.560
So in 47 was it...

00:50:40.560 --> 00:50:44.560
But in those days, see, you had shopping.

00:50:44.560 --> 00:50:48.560
There was a lot more local shops than there is now.

00:50:48.560 --> 00:50:49.560
Yeah.

00:50:50.560 --> 00:50:55.560
So, Mum would go up as far as Kendal's, which was only opposite Lissowerry High School,

00:50:55.560 --> 00:50:57.560
where my grandkids go.

00:50:57.560 --> 00:50:58.560
Yeah.

00:50:58.560 --> 00:51:00.560
Well, and where they went.

00:51:00.560 --> 00:51:01.560
There was the shop there.

00:51:01.560 --> 00:51:02.560
Yeah.

00:51:02.560 --> 00:51:07.560
Kendal's had that shop, and he had the shop farther up, and then the baker was on that

00:51:07.560 --> 00:51:08.560
roundabout by Aldi's.

00:51:08.560 --> 00:51:09.560
Oh, really?

00:51:09.560 --> 00:51:10.560
The baker.

00:51:10.560 --> 00:51:15.560
So you only had to get on the tractor then, you could go in 63, and get the bread out

00:51:15.560 --> 00:51:18.560
of the bakehouse there.

00:51:18.560 --> 00:51:21.560
Mr. Haynes was there, and you'd get the bread off him.

00:51:21.560 --> 00:51:22.560
Yeah.

00:51:22.560 --> 00:51:26.560
I can remember all that before the school was built up there and all.

00:51:26.560 --> 00:51:28.560
Lissowerry School College and all that.

00:51:28.560 --> 00:51:32.560
So all that area, and the area where all that shopping centre is, you know...

00:51:32.560 --> 00:51:33.560
Yeah, it was all farmland.

00:51:33.560 --> 00:51:35.560
That was all farmland.

00:51:35.560 --> 00:51:37.560
That's hard to believe, isn't it?

00:51:37.560 --> 00:51:38.560
It is.

00:51:38.560 --> 00:51:44.560
And when I look at how Newport have grown in all ways, do you know what I mean?

00:51:44.560 --> 00:51:45.560
Yeah, yeah.

00:51:45.560 --> 00:51:52.560
And I'm thinking, well, it was only those houses on Nash Road, as I call Nash Road by

00:51:52.560 --> 00:51:55.560
Lissowerry, there was only the houses there.

00:51:55.560 --> 00:51:57.560
There was nothing behind them.

00:51:57.560 --> 00:52:01.560
Now there's all Pont Fein, what do you call it, Crescent, the other side.

00:52:01.560 --> 00:52:03.560
No, that was all land.

00:52:03.560 --> 00:52:07.560
Well, that was wartime buildings on that side of the road.

00:52:07.560 --> 00:52:08.560
You know those banglows?

00:52:08.560 --> 00:52:09.560
Yeah.

00:52:09.560 --> 00:52:10.560
What do you call them?

00:52:10.560 --> 00:52:11.560
Prefabs.

00:52:11.560 --> 00:52:12.560
Prefabs.

00:52:12.560 --> 00:52:15.560
They were there, and another lot on Chepstow Road.

00:52:15.560 --> 00:52:21.560
But I can remember when I used to go to school, none of Allway or all that was ever built.

00:52:21.560 --> 00:52:22.560
So it was all farmland?

00:52:22.560 --> 00:52:23.560
All farmland, yes.

00:52:23.560 --> 00:52:27.480
The head of the

00:52:27.480 --> 00:52:32.560
There was the Endrew Farm up there, on the left, when you went up there, yeah.

00:52:32.560 --> 00:52:35.560
Because they were butchers in the town.

00:52:35.560 --> 00:52:38.560
Auntie Rose Thompson.

00:52:38.560 --> 00:52:42.560
No relation of ours, but I just had to call her Auntie Rose because she's mam's friend.

00:52:42.560 --> 00:52:47.560
So you're only 78, which isn't that old, and you've seen all these changes.

00:52:47.560 --> 00:52:48.560
Yeah.

00:52:48.560 --> 00:52:51.560
There was none of those houses there when I went to school.

00:52:51.560 --> 00:52:53.560
So it was a very rural area.

00:52:53.560 --> 00:52:58.560
Yeah, it was all rural right up, yeah.

00:52:58.560 --> 00:53:03.560
So did the M4 coming through affect you at all here? Was that noticed?

00:53:03.560 --> 00:53:05.560
No, it was noticed.

00:53:05.560 --> 00:53:06.560
Yeah.

00:53:06.560 --> 00:53:15.560
But that you got off at Magor and then you was like, but the other one that will come through will come not far from Pike Corner, won't it? If it comes.

00:53:15.560 --> 00:53:16.560
If it comes through.

00:53:16.560 --> 00:53:17.560
If it comes through.

00:53:17.560 --> 00:53:19.560
What do you think about that?

00:53:19.560 --> 00:53:26.560
Well, we do need something in Newport because we're gridlocked only nearly all the time now.

00:53:26.560 --> 00:53:32.560
You can be queuing back to Pike Corner to get into town if you don't go early.

00:53:32.560 --> 00:53:33.560
Yes.

00:53:33.560 --> 00:53:40.560
But I think what done that was, they put that road through Lanwerne.

00:53:40.560 --> 00:53:43.560
Well, it brought the traffic quicker, didn't it?

00:53:43.560 --> 00:53:44.560
Yeah.

00:53:44.560 --> 00:53:50.560
I mean, instead of coming along this road, they come straight through now.

00:53:50.560 --> 00:53:56.560
And I think it's quicker. It's got to the bridge and it's jamming us up.

00:53:56.560 --> 00:54:00.560
Do you know what? You see coaches come along our top road now sometimes.

00:54:00.560 --> 00:54:01.560
What, to avoid the traffic?

00:54:01.560 --> 00:54:02.560
To avoid the traffic.

00:54:02.560 --> 00:54:11.560
To avoid the traffic, but they're not getting anywhere because they only turn and before you turn back to go back on or go straight up, you're queuing.

00:54:11.560 --> 00:54:12.560
It's crazy.

00:54:12.560 --> 00:54:18.560
It took me to go to the school. Well, Lane took me up to school because they had a concert on.

00:54:18.560 --> 00:54:25.560
She took the kids up. She said, Mom, hurry up. You're going to have to wait. Come quickly. She said, because we're going queuing.

00:54:25.560 --> 00:54:32.560
It took us three quarters of an hour to do two and a half miles to get to the school.

00:54:32.560 --> 00:54:36.560
It's off walking, aren't you? Really? Or cycling?

00:54:36.560 --> 00:54:37.560
Or cycling.

00:54:37.560 --> 00:54:40.560
Do you know what? I haven't cycled a bike for years. I don't know.

00:54:40.560 --> 00:54:43.560
What about the trains? Did you ever use trains as a child?

00:54:43.560 --> 00:54:52.560
Yes. Dad had to go to Gloucester, look. Pedal up to Lanwerne Station on the bike, get on the train there to Gloucester and do the same coming home.

00:54:52.560 --> 00:54:55.560
Gloucester Market was right by the railway lines in Gloucester, look.

00:54:55.560 --> 00:54:57.560
So I know where Gloucester Market is.

00:54:57.560 --> 00:55:06.560
Oh, where it is now. Oh, where it used to be in the town. Yeah, when Dad would get off the train and you only sort of come down, you were in the market.

00:55:06.560 --> 00:55:08.560
So what if he bought anything?

00:55:08.560 --> 00:55:12.560
Oh, there was always a cattle lorry. No, he didn't have a cattle lorry in the beginning.

00:55:12.560 --> 00:55:15.560
But in the beginning, did they come back on the train with him?

00:55:15.560 --> 00:55:28.560
No. There was a lorry from this area. It was either Mr Arthur, Mr Rees or who else used to fetch it down. But there was always a lorry to bring whenever he bought home.

00:55:28.560 --> 00:55:30.560
And would you ever go with him to Gloucester?

00:55:30.560 --> 00:55:31.560
Yeah.

00:55:31.560 --> 00:55:32.560
Really?

00:55:32.560 --> 00:55:34.560
Yeah, Mam used to want to get rid of me, didn't she?

00:55:34.560 --> 00:55:36.560
So you were both cycled to...

00:55:36.560 --> 00:55:39.560
Lanwerne. Put our bikes in the station.

00:55:39.560 --> 00:55:42.560
Were they trained up then or would you just leave them there?

00:55:42.560 --> 00:55:52.560
No, put them in a little hut in there. And then you'd go on the train, look all the way. Well, Dad had a cousin living just outside Gloucester.

00:55:52.560 --> 00:55:53.560
Yeah.

00:55:53.560 --> 00:55:54.560
In Minsterworth.

00:55:54.560 --> 00:55:55.560
Minsterworth?

00:55:55.560 --> 00:55:56.560
Yeah.

00:55:56.560 --> 00:55:57.560
I was brought up in Minsterworth.

00:55:57.560 --> 00:55:58.560
Were you?

00:55:58.560 --> 00:55:59.560
Yeah, where in Minsterworth?

00:55:59.560 --> 00:56:04.560
Erm, what's the name of it? Well, Harvey's the name was. Do you remember Harvey's?

00:56:04.560 --> 00:56:05.560
Not John Harvey.

00:56:05.560 --> 00:56:07.560
Harvey's the poet?

00:56:07.560 --> 00:56:11.560
No, there was a John and Agnes Harvey who used to run the shop in Minsterworth by the butchers.

00:56:14.560 --> 00:56:18.560
Hunter Gladys she was. She was Dad's first cousin.

00:56:18.560 --> 00:56:19.560
Oh, that's really funny.

00:56:19.560 --> 00:56:21.560
And erm...

00:56:22.560 --> 00:56:24.560
It's on the River Severn.

00:56:24.560 --> 00:56:35.560
Yeah. And she'd come into Gloucester and pick me up and take me back there. And fetch me back if I wanted to come back. She didn't have any children. She was married late in life.

00:56:35.560 --> 00:56:37.560
But her brother was Harvey the poet.

00:56:37.560 --> 00:56:39.560
Harvey the poet? Who's he?

00:56:39.560 --> 00:56:42.560
Yeah, he was a soldier. Remember he was the soldier poet?

00:56:42.560 --> 00:56:43.560
Oh really?

00:56:43.560 --> 00:56:47.560
And he's buried in... yeah, the church up there.

00:56:47.560 --> 00:56:49.560
That's amazing.

00:56:49.560 --> 00:56:52.560
I've got his poetry books upstairs.

00:56:52.560 --> 00:56:53.560
Have you?

00:56:53.560 --> 00:56:54.560
Yeah.

00:56:54.560 --> 00:56:56.560
So this was, well this would have been a steam train and...

00:56:56.560 --> 00:57:04.560
Yeah, yeah, yeah. Go to Gloucester. Dad had fall asleep. It used to worry me. Because I think, well how do you know to get off?

00:57:04.560 --> 00:57:06.560
It was a station. Oh my gosh.

00:57:06.560 --> 00:57:09.560
Yeah, I used to go with him regularly to Gloucester.

00:57:09.560 --> 00:57:12.560
What about the Severn Bridge? Do you remember when that was opened?

00:57:12.560 --> 00:57:14.560
Yes, I remember it being built.

00:57:14.560 --> 00:57:15.560
Do you?

00:57:15.560 --> 00:57:16.560
Yeah.

00:57:17.560 --> 00:57:21.560
Because I would have been about 17 would I then? No.

00:57:21.560 --> 00:57:26.560
Yeah. And does it make a big... I mean what do you remember about it being built?

00:57:26.560 --> 00:57:31.560
Erm... remember that you could go over the other side of the water.

00:57:31.560 --> 00:57:32.560
Yeah.

00:57:32.560 --> 00:57:38.560
Without going all the way up around. Or unless you went over on the...

00:57:38.560 --> 00:57:39.560
Severn Tunnel?

00:57:39.560 --> 00:57:47.560
Yeah. Or... Williamson's Down here used to have a... what do you call it? Take you across on the water. A boat.

00:57:47.560 --> 00:57:48.560
Really?

00:57:48.560 --> 00:57:49.560
Yeah.

00:57:49.560 --> 00:57:50.560
Where from?

00:57:52.560 --> 00:57:59.560
From Chesby. Where the Severn Bridge was. It went down... because I went to school in Chesby. Look, see? So I know all Bullwok and all that.

00:57:59.560 --> 00:58:02.560
And you could take your car on this boat.

00:58:02.560 --> 00:58:03.560
Yeah.

00:58:03.560 --> 00:58:06.560
Oh, God, what was it called?

00:58:06.560 --> 00:58:07.560
Not Oust.

00:58:08.560 --> 00:58:09.560
Oust?

00:58:11.560 --> 00:58:12.560
Port Scuett.

00:58:12.560 --> 00:58:14.560
No, farther up than that.

00:58:14.560 --> 00:58:15.560
Sadbrook.

00:58:16.560 --> 00:58:19.560
No, farther up. It was in Chepstow. It was...

00:58:21.560 --> 00:58:28.560
Well, once the Severn Bridge got built, you know, people never used it. It was like transporting you from this side to the other.

00:58:28.560 --> 00:58:33.560
You drove your car on it and you'd go over the other. It might have been Oust. He was on...

00:58:33.560 --> 00:58:36.560
Yeah, I think there is a famous Oust it is.

00:58:36.560 --> 00:58:42.560
What was it like going across? Because it looks a bit precarious in photographs I've seen.

00:58:42.560 --> 00:58:43.560
I only went over once.

00:58:43.560 --> 00:58:44.560
Really?

00:58:44.560 --> 00:58:55.560
And that was with Geoff's auntie. She took us over on this boat. Well, and drove the car on it. If you went up and it was on it.

00:58:55.560 --> 00:58:57.560
So you said that Williams, they live around here?

00:58:57.560 --> 00:58:58.560
Well, that is the Williams.

00:58:58.560 --> 00:58:59.560
Oh, the Andrean Williams?

00:58:59.560 --> 00:59:00.560
Yeah, his father had it.

00:59:00.560 --> 00:59:02.560
Ah, right, okay.

00:59:02.560 --> 00:59:08.560
He's only moved down here since they sold that up there. Look, he hadn't always been down here. No, it's only like late turn.

00:59:08.560 --> 00:59:15.560
Ah, what about... Would you know the names of all the reams on your land?

00:59:17.560 --> 00:59:18.560
Yes.

00:59:18.560 --> 00:59:19.560
You do? Yeah.

00:59:19.560 --> 00:59:20.560
Yes.

00:59:20.560 --> 00:59:21.560
And what, further afield?

00:59:22.560 --> 00:59:23.560
As far as Redwick.

00:59:24.560 --> 00:59:25.560
As far as... Do you?

00:59:25.560 --> 00:59:26.560
Yeah.

00:59:26.560 --> 00:59:31.560
So when you're driving along in your car, could you say, oh, that's such and such and that's such and such?

00:59:31.560 --> 00:59:32.560
Yeah.

00:59:32.560 --> 00:59:35.560
Could you? That's really impressive.

00:59:35.560 --> 00:59:38.560
Yeah, because, like, Dad was from Redwick.

00:59:38.560 --> 00:59:39.560
Yeah.

00:59:39.560 --> 00:59:49.560
Um, I suppose Redwick, although I've always lived here, born here and all that, I've always got a love for Redwick.

00:59:49.560 --> 00:59:55.560
I suppose because Dad's... My two brothers are buried here. One is buried over here, don't they?

00:59:55.560 --> 00:59:57.560
Did you marry there?

00:59:57.560 --> 01:00:00.560
Yes. Yes, in Redwick Church.

01:00:02.560 --> 01:00:04.560
Do you remember the shop then? The little shop?

01:00:04.560 --> 01:00:06.560
Yes, on the bottom by the crossroads.

01:00:06.560 --> 01:00:10.560
Yeah, run by one of the howls, was it?

01:00:10.560 --> 01:00:16.560
Yes. Now... Hang on.

01:00:16.560 --> 01:00:22.560
Um, yes, Howells's mother had it, wasn't it? Mrs. Howells's mother.

01:00:22.560 --> 01:00:25.560
Mrs. Howells's grandmother. Duck Howells's grandmother, I think, had it.

01:00:25.560 --> 01:00:26.560
Yeah.

01:00:26.560 --> 01:00:28.560
I think, or something like that.

01:00:28.560 --> 01:00:32.560
Now, wasn't the daughter there adopted or a niece?

01:00:32.560 --> 01:00:34.560
Yes. Yes. His mother was adopted, yeah.

01:00:34.560 --> 01:00:35.560
Yeah, that's it.

01:00:35.560 --> 01:00:36.560
Yeah.

01:00:36.560 --> 01:00:37.560
What was her name?

01:00:37.560 --> 01:00:45.560
Oh, I used to go to that shop because when I said to you about Auntie Daisy, if on light nights you were in the shop,

01:00:45.560 --> 01:00:52.560
you know, you could walk across the Islet ground, as I call it, up Mead Lane.

01:00:52.560 --> 01:00:53.560
Yeah.

01:00:53.560 --> 01:00:57.560
And then you came out by the church and then just walked along there.

01:00:57.560 --> 01:01:03.560
And then she'd buy me some sweets and we'd get her a bit of shopping, then we'd walk back down the Islet.

01:01:03.560 --> 01:01:07.560
And I tell you what we used to do, I don't know if we're allowed to do it today.

01:01:07.560 --> 01:01:11.560
In the Islet ground, there were lovely cow slips.

01:01:11.560 --> 01:01:15.560
Cow slips. So I always used to pick a bunch of cow slips from them.

01:01:15.560 --> 01:01:17.560
But you're not supposed to pick them today, are you?

01:01:17.560 --> 01:01:19.560
Oh, really? How lovely.

01:01:19.560 --> 01:01:25.560
Oh, it was full of cow slips. The Island ground was, and the Island ground is right at the bottom.

01:01:25.560 --> 01:01:34.560
When Mead Lane comes into the steelworks, which they made the road down there, you just go that way, through that gateway,

01:01:34.560 --> 01:01:37.560
and two fields in was the Island ground.

01:01:37.560 --> 01:01:38.560
The Highland ground?

01:01:38.560 --> 01:01:40.560
Yeah, it was called the Island ground.

01:01:40.560 --> 01:01:41.560
Why was it called that?

01:01:41.560 --> 01:01:45.560
Well, it had a little bit of a mound in it or something.

01:01:45.560 --> 01:01:48.560
And they picked some cow slips when they were out.

01:01:48.560 --> 01:01:51.560
Never dug any up mine or nothing like that.

01:01:51.560 --> 01:01:54.560
But you're not supposed to pick them today, are you?

01:01:54.560 --> 01:01:57.560
I mowed some in my garden the other day.

01:01:57.560 --> 01:01:59.560
Well, they were just going over.

01:01:59.560 --> 01:02:04.560
Oh, going over. But I don't think you're supposed to pick them though.

01:02:04.560 --> 01:02:06.560
Oh, you lovely, lovely, pretty, fetch on for a man.

01:02:06.560 --> 01:02:09.560
They were so pretty. I used to suck the honey out of them.

01:02:09.560 --> 01:02:11.560
Oh yes, you could, yeah.

01:02:11.560 --> 01:02:20.560
Oh, there are other things, like wildlife and things that you used to see when you were a child that you don't see now at the levels.

01:02:20.560 --> 01:02:23.560
For example, I've spoken to people who...

01:02:23.560 --> 01:02:27.560
Curly, I don't think I see so much as I used to. You know, they had a...

01:02:27.560 --> 01:02:29.560
Yeah.

01:02:29.560 --> 01:02:32.560
I don't see so much of them.

01:02:32.560 --> 01:02:33.560
Hairs?

01:02:33.560 --> 01:02:35.560
Oh, I've got quite a few hairs.

01:02:35.560 --> 01:02:36.560
Oh, yeah.

01:02:36.560 --> 01:02:39.560
Oh, that's lovely. Oh, that's lovely.

01:02:39.560 --> 01:02:44.560
I love them. And they seem to...

01:02:44.560 --> 01:02:49.560
Well, they do breed in where you leave a little bit of long grass.

01:02:49.560 --> 01:02:59.560
And we've always left at the bottom, and by the 10 acres, a little bit of long grass and tidy grass.

01:02:59.560 --> 01:03:02.560
It looks untidy, but it's left there.

01:03:02.560 --> 01:03:05.560
Because that's where...

01:03:05.560 --> 01:03:09.560
I don't see so many partridges as we used to, neither.

01:03:09.560 --> 01:03:10.560
Yeah.

01:03:10.560 --> 01:03:14.560
Because they used to hatch a lot on the fields, don't you?

01:03:14.560 --> 01:03:16.560
Oh, really?

01:03:16.560 --> 01:03:19.560
Did you ever get otters down here?

01:03:19.560 --> 01:03:22.560
We've got otters, yes, but we've got otters coming back now.

01:03:22.560 --> 01:03:24.560
Yeah.

01:03:24.560 --> 01:03:27.560
I'd seen one the other day in Chaperwene.

01:03:27.560 --> 01:03:28.560
Did you?

01:03:28.560 --> 01:03:33.560
Apparently, they're... I couldn't make out what it was.

01:03:33.560 --> 01:03:36.560
I thought, that's not a mink.

01:03:36.560 --> 01:03:41.560
Because we did have mink, you know, where somebody had let some go or something.

01:03:41.560 --> 01:03:42.560
Were they a problem for you?

01:03:42.560 --> 01:03:46.560
Yeah, well, they'd get in, and we only got a few chicken.

01:03:46.560 --> 01:03:52.560
But, you know, they seemed to burrow their ways into the chicken houses if they got no bones then,

01:03:52.560 --> 01:03:55.560
and they couldn't get into any little hole.

01:03:55.560 --> 01:03:59.560
We had one, and we only had six chicken hen in a chicken house and killed a lot.

01:03:59.560 --> 01:04:00.560
Oh, no.

01:04:00.560 --> 01:04:02.560
And we had seen one.

01:04:02.560 --> 01:04:07.560
We don't know whether it done it, but we'd seen one coming across our pond,

01:04:07.560 --> 01:04:10.560
where they were used on the lane.

01:04:10.560 --> 01:04:11.560
And I shut them in.

01:04:11.560 --> 01:04:17.560
I know I shut the door and all that night and went to let them go next morning.

01:04:17.560 --> 01:04:20.560
And they were all dead in there.

01:04:20.560 --> 01:04:26.560
No, well, and it was only a little hole about that big that he burrowed through.

01:04:26.560 --> 01:04:28.560
Yeah, they're slinky.

01:04:28.560 --> 01:04:30.560
Yeah, like if they got no bones.

01:04:30.560 --> 01:04:35.560
And we blamed it on the mink anyway.

01:04:35.560 --> 01:04:40.560
Did you? I was talking to somebody the other day over towards Peterstone,

01:04:40.560 --> 01:04:45.560
and she remembers as a child seeing the otter hounds down there.

01:04:45.560 --> 01:04:46.560
Yes.

01:04:46.560 --> 01:04:47.560
Did you ever have them here?

01:04:47.560 --> 01:04:56.560
Yes, but they didn't do much good our side because I think our ditches are a bit deeper than the other side.

01:04:56.560 --> 01:05:03.560
They came twice, the otters, and they didn't have anything.

01:05:03.560 --> 01:05:05.560
They didn't see anything, they said.

01:05:05.560 --> 01:05:10.560
But I think the ditches are a bit more deeper our side than...

01:05:10.560 --> 01:05:12.560
Do you remember what they wore?

01:05:12.560 --> 01:05:17.560
Was it blue and red stockings, I wonder?

01:05:17.560 --> 01:05:25.560
Or was it red tops on stockings? Was it all red?

01:05:25.560 --> 01:05:30.560
Oh, that's interesting they were here.

01:05:30.560 --> 01:05:32.560
What about the beagles?

01:05:32.560 --> 01:05:37.560
Yeah, but they're no good from down here because of the water.

01:05:37.560 --> 01:05:38.560
Oh, really?

01:05:38.560 --> 01:05:42.560
They can't, you know, they can't get going.

01:05:42.560 --> 01:05:46.560
They do come down Greenmoor, they meet once a year.

01:05:46.560 --> 01:05:47.560
Yes.

01:05:47.560 --> 01:05:54.560
And that all comes down at Harrison, I think it is, fetches them down.

01:05:54.560 --> 01:05:58.560
But they chase, but the fox, they always gets away.

01:05:58.560 --> 01:06:00.560
Because they can jump the water, can't they?

01:06:00.560 --> 01:06:06.560
And the owls before they can get whatever they are on the trace, they can't do it, you know.

01:06:06.560 --> 01:06:10.560
I mean they couldn't use horses down here, they could only walk in any case.

01:06:10.560 --> 01:06:15.560
The thing that interests me, Cath, is this area, is that high tide you're below sea level.

01:06:15.560 --> 01:06:16.560
Sea level, yeah.

01:06:16.560 --> 01:06:19.560
Do you ever think about that? Does it ever worry you?

01:06:19.560 --> 01:06:20.560
No.

01:06:20.560 --> 01:06:21.560
No?

01:06:21.560 --> 01:06:23.560
Never think about it, no.

01:06:23.560 --> 01:06:26.560
And have you ever seen floods here?

01:06:26.560 --> 01:06:27.560
Yes.

01:06:27.560 --> 01:06:28.560
Coming over the wall?

01:06:28.560 --> 01:06:33.560
Yes. And we have been flooded here where we couldn't get out.

01:06:33.560 --> 01:06:34.560
Really?

01:06:34.560 --> 01:06:37.560
One was up to our gate that comes on the back.

01:06:37.560 --> 01:06:38.560
Yeah.

01:06:38.560 --> 01:06:45.560
And all Chapel Road in the low bits then was all flooded over, you know, we couldn't either...

01:06:45.560 --> 01:06:49.560
Yeah, we have been flooded here, but never up to the house.

01:06:49.560 --> 01:06:52.560
But we never think of...

01:06:52.560 --> 01:06:55.560
Oh, we'd have to get a boat, wouldn't we?

01:06:55.560 --> 01:07:00.560
Never think of being actual flooded.

01:07:00.560 --> 01:07:04.560
When was the Great Floods?

01:07:04.560 --> 01:07:05.560
Well, you mean...

01:07:05.560 --> 01:07:07.560
In the churches and all that.

01:07:07.560 --> 01:07:09.560
1606 I think it was.

01:07:09.560 --> 01:07:12.560
Yeah, because they say that was a tsunami, don't they, already?

01:07:12.560 --> 01:07:13.560
Yeah.

01:07:13.560 --> 01:07:15.560
Yeah, no, I didn't see that.

01:07:15.560 --> 01:07:18.560
So what caused the flood that time then, when you were here?

01:07:18.560 --> 01:07:21.560
It was coming over the wall.

01:07:21.560 --> 01:07:26.560
And I tell you, one day we went up...

01:07:26.560 --> 01:07:28.560
Was it Linmouth got flooded?

01:07:28.560 --> 01:07:29.560
Yes.

01:07:29.560 --> 01:07:35.560
Well, I shouldn't say it, but it was a good job, because that night we went to see it,

01:07:35.560 --> 01:07:38.560
because it was lapping over the wall, and we went to see it down the corridor, because

01:07:38.560 --> 01:07:43.560
we got land on the corridor, steelworks, you know, which goes to the sea wall.

01:07:43.560 --> 01:07:48.560
And we went up there and it was just about to come over the wall.

01:07:48.560 --> 01:07:54.560
And then next day, because I thought, oh Jesus, we've got land, we've got cattle down here.

01:07:54.560 --> 01:07:56.560
That must be so daunting seeing that.

01:07:56.560 --> 01:07:58.560
I was worried about the cattle, you know.

01:07:58.560 --> 01:08:02.560
Well, then next day on the news, when I put on the wireless, Linmouth had had it, and

01:08:02.560 --> 01:08:05.560
I thought, oh thank God it went that way and not our way.

01:08:05.560 --> 01:08:09.560
Because I mean, we're more or less opposite of it.

01:08:09.560 --> 01:08:10.560
Yeah.

01:08:10.560 --> 01:08:14.560
That we would have had it then, because we went down just to see and sit on the wall

01:08:14.560 --> 01:08:19.560
to see what was happening, and it was just about that much starting to...

01:08:19.560 --> 01:08:20.560
Yeah.

01:08:20.560 --> 01:08:25.560
Do you keep an eye on weather conditions then, just in case of the high tides and...

01:08:25.560 --> 01:08:29.560
Well, they are looking after us quite well now.

01:08:29.560 --> 01:08:30.560
Yeah.

01:08:30.560 --> 01:08:35.560
They do put the boards, if it's going to be really to stop it coming up.

01:08:35.560 --> 01:08:36.560
Yeah.

01:08:36.560 --> 01:08:37.560
But if the boards...

01:08:37.560 --> 01:08:39.560
Well, no, we've got new boards now, haven't we?

01:08:39.560 --> 01:08:41.560
Yes, where they wind them.

01:08:44.560 --> 01:08:49.560
You could get salt water right up through Chapel Ream when the tides was really going,

01:08:49.560 --> 01:08:54.560
when we had the old boards, because I think the weight and the drift of it would move them.

01:08:54.560 --> 01:08:58.560
Oh yeah, you get salt water right past us here.

01:08:58.560 --> 01:08:59.560
Really?

01:08:59.560 --> 01:09:00.560
Crikey.

01:09:00.560 --> 01:09:02.560
So how far are we from the seawall here?

01:09:02.560 --> 01:09:03.560
What would it be?

01:09:03.560 --> 01:09:05.560
About a mile and a half, we're really...

01:09:05.560 --> 01:09:06.560
Crikey.

01:09:06.560 --> 01:09:07.560
Right down the road.

01:09:07.560 --> 01:09:08.560
Yeah.

01:09:08.560 --> 01:09:09.560
Yeah, because there's one at the bottom there, isn't there?

01:09:09.560 --> 01:09:10.560
The gout.

01:09:10.560 --> 01:09:11.560
Yeah.

01:09:11.560 --> 01:09:13.560
Oh no, there's no wall there, is there?

01:09:13.560 --> 01:09:15.560
It's just a filter off, isn't there?

01:09:15.560 --> 01:09:18.560
So do you still have grips on your land?

01:09:18.560 --> 01:09:19.560
Yeah.

01:09:19.560 --> 01:09:20.560
Yeah.

01:09:20.560 --> 01:09:21.560
Still got the old grips.

01:09:21.560 --> 01:09:23.560
We've never been drained, you know.

01:09:23.560 --> 01:09:25.560
Because they work effectively for you.

01:09:25.560 --> 01:09:28.560
Yeah, when your grip's full up, you know, go on the end.

01:09:28.560 --> 01:09:33.560
But I tell them it's the tractors they're driving that cracks the pipes on the end.

01:09:33.560 --> 01:09:34.560
Do you think so?

01:09:34.560 --> 01:09:37.560
Well, it's got to be weight on it.

01:09:37.560 --> 01:09:39.560
It only used to be cows or horses, didn't it?

01:09:39.560 --> 01:09:43.560
Or, well, the tractors are getting heavier and heavier.

01:09:43.560 --> 01:09:44.560
And bigger and bigger.

01:09:44.560 --> 01:09:45.560
Bigger, yeah.

01:09:45.560 --> 01:09:47.560
So in your father's time, was it still horse drawn?

01:09:47.560 --> 01:09:48.560
Yeah.

01:09:48.560 --> 01:09:49.560
Do you remember that?

01:09:49.560 --> 01:09:50.560
Yeah.

01:09:50.560 --> 01:09:51.560
Do you?

01:09:51.560 --> 01:09:52.560
Yeah, I used to ride the horse.

01:09:52.560 --> 01:09:53.560
We had a horse.

01:09:53.560 --> 01:09:56.560
They'd make the A-Ricks in the field.

01:09:56.560 --> 01:09:57.560
Yeah.

01:09:57.560 --> 01:10:00.560
And they used to have a horse in front of it like a wooden sweep.

01:10:00.560 --> 01:10:01.560
Yeah.

01:10:01.560 --> 01:10:05.560
And they'd row it up and the horse would be pulling it up.

01:10:05.560 --> 01:10:07.560
Yeah, Dad used to chuck me on there, put me on their backs.

01:10:07.560 --> 01:10:08.560
Really?

01:10:08.560 --> 01:10:10.560
To ride the horse down.

01:10:10.560 --> 01:10:16.560
So are there any words that you've used around here that might not be used anywhere else?

01:10:16.560 --> 01:10:20.560
I never thought of that.

01:10:20.560 --> 01:10:27.560
All traditions or myths or ghost stories or folk stories.

01:10:27.560 --> 01:10:30.560
I did love the folk stories.

01:10:30.560 --> 01:10:38.560
But I don't know.

01:10:38.560 --> 01:10:41.560
Any old characters that you remember around here?

01:10:41.560 --> 01:10:47.560
Yes, old Mad Jack, Derby Joe, old Bob Groves.

01:10:47.560 --> 01:10:48.560
Who were they?

01:10:48.560 --> 01:10:54.560
They used to come around when you were busy and live in your couch head or something like

01:10:54.560 --> 01:10:57.560
that and have food and do work on the farms.

01:10:57.560 --> 01:10:58.560
Really?

01:10:58.560 --> 01:10:59.560
Yeah.

01:10:59.560 --> 01:11:00.560
Do you know where they...

01:11:00.560 --> 01:11:01.560
Bill Newport.

01:11:01.560 --> 01:11:03.560
There was lots of them.

01:11:03.560 --> 01:11:08.560
Do you know where they came from or anything like that and their background?

01:11:08.560 --> 01:11:09.560
No.

01:11:09.560 --> 01:11:10.560
No?

01:11:10.560 --> 01:11:11.560
No.

01:11:11.560 --> 01:11:15.560
Are you too young to remember the war?

01:11:15.560 --> 01:11:17.560
Yeah, I was born in 41.

01:11:17.560 --> 01:11:18.560
So you wouldn't remember?

01:11:18.560 --> 01:11:21.560
I was born when it was...

01:11:21.560 --> 01:11:23.560
Apparently...

01:11:23.560 --> 01:11:26.560
Well, this house here had all the windows...

01:11:26.560 --> 01:11:32.560
Bombs dropped on the shed on the end of the house and blew all the windows in.

01:11:32.560 --> 01:11:36.560
Mamma always used to...

01:11:36.560 --> 01:11:38.560
Oh, don't it sound daft.

01:11:38.560 --> 01:11:40.560
Put us under the kitchen table.

01:11:40.560 --> 01:11:43.560
I've heard that from several people actually.

01:11:43.560 --> 01:11:45.560
But it does sound daft, doesn't it?

01:11:45.560 --> 01:11:47.560
What would the kitchen table do?

01:11:47.560 --> 01:11:50.560
And we still got the same table in the kitchen now.

01:11:50.560 --> 01:11:51.560
You haven't.

01:11:51.560 --> 01:11:52.560
I have.

01:11:52.560 --> 01:11:53.560
It was a good table then.

01:11:53.560 --> 01:11:55.560
Yeah, I'll show it to you.

01:11:55.560 --> 01:11:59.560
In my kitchen there, the table...

01:11:59.560 --> 01:12:04.560
It's the table I can always remember.

01:12:04.560 --> 01:12:05.560
What?

01:12:05.560 --> 01:12:10.560
From a kid sat at the same table.

01:12:10.560 --> 01:12:12.560
So would you...

01:12:12.560 --> 01:12:14.560
We haven't altered it a lot.

01:12:14.560 --> 01:12:15.560
Do you know what I mean?

01:12:15.560 --> 01:12:16.560
Yeah.

01:12:16.560 --> 01:12:19.560
I've got a junk room upstairs.

01:12:19.560 --> 01:12:21.560
I expect everybody have.

01:12:21.560 --> 01:12:25.560
Which...

01:12:25.560 --> 01:12:29.560
Lots of things in there.

01:12:29.560 --> 01:12:34.560
I got lots of photographs too when I get down to digging around in there.

01:12:34.560 --> 01:12:38.560
If you have any photographs, I would love to see them.

01:12:38.560 --> 01:12:41.560
Yeah, I got photographs up there.

01:12:41.560 --> 01:12:43.560
Yeah, you might need to dig around for them.

01:12:43.560 --> 01:12:49.560
Yeah.

01:12:49.560 --> 01:12:56.560
So what is it? What's special about this place, this area?

01:12:56.560 --> 01:12:58.560
What's special?

01:12:58.560 --> 01:13:00.560
Well, I think it's special because we got...

01:13:00.560 --> 01:13:05.560
On the part of the farm here too, we've got an ancient monument where you can't dig.

01:13:05.560 --> 01:13:09.560
It's like a tent where they say it was a burial ground.

01:13:09.560 --> 01:13:10.560
Really?

01:13:10.560 --> 01:13:11.560
So you don't touch it.

01:13:11.560 --> 01:13:15.560
You can't blow it. You don't do anything to it. You can mow it. You can graze it.

01:13:15.560 --> 01:13:19.560
But you're not allowed to...

01:13:19.560 --> 01:13:20.560
Disturb it?

01:13:20.560 --> 01:13:23.560
No, you're not allowed to do a... What do they do? Metal detector?

01:13:23.560 --> 01:13:25.560
You're not allowed to do anything.

01:13:25.560 --> 01:13:30.560
That's by the cottage that joins us on the far end of the farm.

01:13:30.560 --> 01:13:37.560
Apparently it was the man from the ancient monument's core one day.

01:13:37.560 --> 01:13:42.560
And I think he... Yeah, he did. He gave me photographs of what it looked like.

01:13:42.560 --> 01:13:43.560
Yeah.

01:13:43.560 --> 01:13:45.560
And was it TP's or something?

01:13:45.560 --> 01:13:46.560
Yeah.

01:13:46.560 --> 01:13:50.560
That was on there. And he said, it's a burial ground there.

01:13:50.560 --> 01:13:53.560
And I said, oh!

01:13:53.560 --> 01:13:58.560
And laughed. He said, you're not allowed to touch it, he said. You're not allowed to level it off.

01:13:58.560 --> 01:14:05.560
The field sort of... It's that high and then it seems to go in a dip.

01:14:05.560 --> 01:14:07.560
I wonder how old is it?

01:14:07.560 --> 01:14:08.560
Oh, it's old.

01:14:08.560 --> 01:14:09.560
Yeah.

01:14:09.560 --> 01:14:12.560
But we're not allowed to touch anything.

01:14:12.560 --> 01:14:16.560
He comes and checks the house, mine, because this is a grade two listed building.

01:14:16.560 --> 01:14:20.560
Is it? How old is it?

01:14:20.560 --> 01:14:24.560
It's on the front. I think a bit was rebuilt. 18 something.

01:14:24.560 --> 01:14:26.560
Oh gosh.

01:14:26.560 --> 01:14:31.560
Oh yeah, because there, that's got to stay there. Look, that wall there.

01:14:31.560 --> 01:14:34.560
That's years ago. They kept cows in there.

01:14:34.560 --> 01:14:35.560
Oh really?

01:14:35.560 --> 01:14:36.560
Next door then.

01:14:36.560 --> 01:14:37.560
Yeah.

01:14:37.560 --> 01:14:41.560
And that was, was it a filter through? And you see where the bricks are on the top?

01:14:41.560 --> 01:14:42.560
Yeah.

01:14:42.560 --> 01:14:45.560
They used to put the fodder out through there to feed the animals the other side of the wall.

01:14:45.560 --> 01:14:46.560
Oh my god.

01:14:46.560 --> 01:14:48.560
But that's the old beam and...

01:14:48.560 --> 01:14:51.560
So that's new, that bit in there?

01:14:51.560 --> 01:14:56.560
No, that was the old cellar. Look, the old flagstone stay you got to...

01:14:56.560 --> 01:14:57.560
Oh my god.

01:14:57.560 --> 01:15:03.560
The food is there. There's a slab there, look, where they used to salt the...

01:15:03.560 --> 01:15:07.560
Yeah, you have to get up. You have to get up.

01:15:07.560 --> 01:15:08.560
Isn't that awful?

01:15:08.560 --> 01:15:09.560
Just round here?

01:15:09.560 --> 01:15:11.560
Yeah, see where the television is?

01:15:11.560 --> 01:15:13.560
Oh, that's where they used to salt the pig?

01:15:13.560 --> 01:15:14.560
Yeah.

01:15:14.560 --> 01:15:15.560
You still got that?

01:15:15.560 --> 01:15:16.560
Yeah.

01:15:16.560 --> 01:15:19.560
That's amazing. Wow.

01:15:19.560 --> 01:15:20.560
That's the...

01:15:20.560 --> 01:15:22.560
Doesn't it have an orchard here?

01:15:22.560 --> 01:15:24.560
Yeah, the orchard's out there.

01:15:24.560 --> 01:15:25.560
Is it still there now?

01:15:25.560 --> 01:15:26.560
Yeah.

01:15:26.560 --> 01:15:27.560
Oh, that is?

01:15:27.560 --> 01:15:33.560
Oh my god. When I was a kid there was trees I used to climb up and they're still there.

01:15:33.560 --> 01:15:35.560
So...

01:15:35.560 --> 01:15:38.560
It's got to be...

01:15:38.560 --> 01:15:42.560
I don't know. 70 years or more, isn't it?

01:15:42.560 --> 01:15:44.560
So did you ever have a cider press here?

01:15:44.560 --> 01:15:48.560
Yeah. Well, yeah, there was a cider press but we used to have a travelling press.

01:15:48.560 --> 01:15:53.560
A man come around and do the cider in the front yard, I got photographs of that somewhere.

01:15:53.560 --> 01:15:54.560
Melville Jones.

01:15:54.560 --> 01:15:55.560
That's the one!

01:15:55.560 --> 01:15:56.560
Yeah.

01:15:56.560 --> 01:15:58.560
Who was he then? Was he a local?

01:15:58.560 --> 01:16:05.560
Local and he travelled the press and he'd do it with... they'd pick the apples and they'd put them in and press it down.

01:16:05.560 --> 01:16:09.560
The cider went in like a troll. I can remember all that.

01:16:09.560 --> 01:16:12.560
Oh, if you find those photographs I would love to see them.

01:16:12.560 --> 01:16:13.560
I know, I can.

01:16:13.560 --> 01:16:16.560
Yeah. Yeah.

01:16:16.560 --> 01:16:18.560
Give me time.

01:16:18.560 --> 01:16:23.560
Is there anything else you'd like to add, Kath?

01:16:23.560 --> 01:16:27.560
Oh, I don't think so. I don't know. There's lots of things that you think of them.

01:16:27.560 --> 01:16:29.560
Yeah. Oh, did you ever go to Whitsun Sioux?

01:16:29.560 --> 01:16:33.560
Yes, Mrs Mayberry, Whitsun Sioux, yes.

01:16:33.560 --> 01:16:34.560
It was lovely.

01:16:34.560 --> 01:16:35.560
Yeah.

01:16:35.560 --> 01:16:36.560
She was a lovely old lady.

01:16:36.560 --> 01:16:37.560
Was she?

01:16:37.560 --> 01:16:38.560
Oh, she was lovely.

01:16:38.560 --> 01:16:39.560
Yeah.

01:16:39.560 --> 01:16:42.560
And in her latter years she had a deer at the Sioux, right?

01:16:42.560 --> 01:16:43.560
Yeah.

01:16:43.560 --> 01:16:48.560
And she had to keep it tethered down because every time she'd let it go it landed here with us.

01:16:48.560 --> 01:16:50.560
In the end she'd give it to us.

01:16:50.560 --> 01:16:51.560
She gave you the deer?

01:16:51.560 --> 01:16:57.560
Yeah. Well, it stayed with our cattle. We fed it in the shed and all. It would stay with her.

01:16:57.560 --> 01:17:01.560
And she'd be fed up coming to get it and then they tethered it over there.

01:17:01.560 --> 01:17:03.560
But it was coming up here to you?

01:17:03.560 --> 01:17:09.560
Yes, it was coming across the hills. Because like the Sioux was already just like there across.

01:17:09.560 --> 01:17:10.560
Yeah.

01:17:10.560 --> 01:17:17.560
And it stayed with our cattle all the time. And she said in the end, she said, oh, I'm going to give you the deer.

01:17:17.560 --> 01:17:24.560
She said, leave it home. And never left us. It died in the shed up the common. Happy with us. Never bothered as long as we were there.

01:17:24.560 --> 01:17:32.560
And what used to amuse me, she used to take all, if you had an animal die, you took it over to her and she'd put it into the lions.

01:17:32.560 --> 01:17:33.560
She had lions there.

01:17:33.560 --> 01:17:35.560
Yes, yes, I heard that, yeah.

01:17:35.560 --> 01:17:39.560
But oh, she had to keep these lions in. Oh, a good fence around there, yeah.

01:17:39.560 --> 01:17:40.560
Yeah.

01:17:40.560 --> 01:17:47.560
But like the old fashioned chain arrows, you know, what they pull behind the level of ground.

01:17:47.560 --> 01:17:54.560
And then I'll always remember, she used to open up, we used to get money for the church.

01:17:54.560 --> 01:18:00.560
She did and all that. She'd open one of her rooms and we'd play whist in the house there.

01:18:00.560 --> 01:18:07.560
Yeah, about once a month she'd have us playing whist. We'd be playing whist and all the money went to charity.

01:18:07.560 --> 01:18:09.560
She was lovely.

01:18:09.560 --> 01:18:10.560
And...

01:18:10.560 --> 01:18:12.560
Did you see the lions and the bears there?

01:18:12.560 --> 01:18:15.560
Yes. Yeah, well, no, this is what I was going to tell you.

01:18:15.560 --> 01:18:22.560
She had, people used to take, they used to have trips out from town, you know, to see them.

01:18:22.560 --> 01:18:27.560
Well, of course, she put the two bears together this day when this trip was coming.

01:18:27.560 --> 01:18:33.560
Well, they arrived and all of a sudden they started to fight and one nearly killed the other.

01:18:33.560 --> 01:18:38.560
But the two bears did together. Oh, she was a lovely lady.

01:18:38.560 --> 01:18:43.560
I mean, someone was telling me over at Porton that they could sometimes hear the lion roar.

01:18:43.560 --> 01:18:46.560
Yeah, we heard you when the wind was in our direction.

01:18:46.560 --> 01:18:47.560
Really?

01:18:47.560 --> 01:18:54.560
And she had peacocks and all their luck. Well, you could hear them squawking. Monkeys she had, she had everything.

01:18:54.560 --> 01:19:01.560
And I'll always remember this one day. The monkeys had broke out.

01:19:01.560 --> 01:19:02.560
Yeah, yeah.

01:19:02.560 --> 01:19:05.560
Yeah? Well, the vet had to come to shoot them and we were having to...

01:19:05.560 --> 01:19:07.560
Who was the vet then?

01:19:07.560 --> 01:19:12.560
What are you doing down here with the gun? Why I didn't want to see you, Kathy, he said.

01:19:12.560 --> 01:19:18.560
What are you doing? He said, I've got to shoot, there's a couple monkeys up the tree over there.

01:19:18.560 --> 01:19:21.560
He said, and I'm going to go shoot these monkeys.

01:19:21.560 --> 01:19:26.560
And we laughed, I didn't believe him. And he said, yeah.

01:19:26.560 --> 01:19:31.560
All right, then I said, we'll sit on the road and wait. No, we'll come back along after and see if you had them.

01:19:31.560 --> 01:19:36.560
Yeah, you shot him. I said two or three, he chopped these monkeys.

01:19:36.560 --> 01:19:37.560
I think Margaret was telling me that.

01:19:37.560 --> 01:19:38.560
Yeah.

01:19:38.560 --> 01:19:42.560
Just going back to the cider, so did your dad make cider?

01:19:42.560 --> 01:19:43.560
Yeah.

01:19:43.560 --> 01:19:44.560
Where did he keep it?

01:19:44.560 --> 01:19:54.560
Yeah, where that kitchen is there. That was the cider casks used to be on things and barrels. I still got a couple of them.

01:19:54.560 --> 01:19:55.560
Really?

01:19:55.560 --> 01:19:57.560
The taps that you tap into the...

01:19:57.560 --> 01:20:00.560
And was it just for your own consumption?

01:20:00.560 --> 01:20:12.560
Well, yeah, but everybody had come here and sort of had cider. I can remember about four or five, they'd arrive and they'd be drinking cider and not drunk.

01:20:12.560 --> 01:20:13.560
Yeah, just sociable.

01:20:13.560 --> 01:20:14.560
Yeah.

01:20:14.560 --> 01:20:15.560
Yeah.

01:20:15.560 --> 01:20:24.560
And I think, yes, dad used to play, because he used to come from Redwick to you as well.

01:20:24.560 --> 01:20:25.560
Yeah.

01:20:25.560 --> 01:20:29.560
What did he use to play? A game called Penny something?

01:20:29.560 --> 01:20:30.560
Shove Penny.

01:20:30.560 --> 01:20:31.560
Shove Penny.

01:20:31.560 --> 01:20:32.560
Really?

01:20:32.560 --> 01:20:36.560
And I think they used to play with, you know...

01:20:36.560 --> 01:20:40.560
This must have been a fantastic place to grow up in here.

01:20:40.560 --> 01:20:42.560
You know, there's lots of things.

01:20:42.560 --> 01:20:45.560
He sounds like quite a character.

01:20:45.560 --> 01:20:56.560
Yeah, he was. He went to town, somebody brought a rabbit for me. Oh, hang on, I think it was...

01:20:56.560 --> 01:21:02.560
Oh, I can't think of her name now, but I always wanted a rabbit, right?

01:21:02.560 --> 01:21:12.560
So on a Wednesday, he said when he left, he was... this lady, oh, God, I don't know what her name was, bringing me in a rabbit.

01:21:12.560 --> 01:21:16.560
Well, dad used to ride his bike to Newport Market, look, before we had a car.

01:21:16.560 --> 01:21:17.560
Yeah.

01:21:17.560 --> 01:21:18.560
Right?

01:21:18.560 --> 01:21:19.560
Yeah.

01:21:19.560 --> 01:21:27.560
Well, it wasn't far up there. And he took a bag with him, or a frame or a bag on the bike, right?

01:21:27.560 --> 01:21:30.560
Well, then he'd gone and had a drink in the White Hart pub.

01:21:30.560 --> 01:21:31.560
Yeah.

01:21:31.560 --> 01:21:42.560
Well, coming home with the rabbit on the bike, he killed my rabbit because he fell off the bike or the bag got caught in the wheel. I cried my eyes out.

01:21:42.560 --> 01:21:43.560
Oh, my goodness.

01:21:43.560 --> 01:21:44.560
Yeah.

01:21:44.560 --> 01:21:45.560
Oh, my goodness.

01:21:45.560 --> 01:21:47.560
I shouldn't laugh, really.

01:21:47.560 --> 01:21:53.560
No, I didn't at the time because I broke my heart. I was looking forward to this rabbit. They'd even made me a little wooden hatch.

01:21:53.560 --> 01:21:59.560
But the rabbit... I think it had either got caught in the wheel or...

01:21:59.560 --> 01:22:00.560
One of the others.

01:22:00.560 --> 01:22:01.560
Yeah.

01:22:01.560 --> 01:22:02.560
Yeah.

01:22:02.560 --> 01:22:04.560
And he brought the dead rabbit home.

01:22:04.560 --> 01:22:05.560
Oh.

01:22:05.560 --> 01:22:07.560
Baby chicken in the garden.

01:22:07.560 --> 01:22:08.560
Oh, my goodness.

01:22:08.560 --> 01:22:11.560
Yeah, oh, hi, the shawls and the rabbit.

01:22:11.560 --> 01:22:13.560
So was there a livestock market in Newport?

01:22:13.560 --> 01:22:14.560
Yeah.

01:22:14.560 --> 01:22:15.560
Was it a big one?

01:22:15.560 --> 01:22:19.560
Yeah. Yeah. Well, I used to go to it.

01:22:19.560 --> 01:22:21.560
Did you cycle with your dad?

01:22:21.560 --> 01:22:28.560
Yeah. And then when my two brothers died, look, I was left here then to farm the thing.

01:22:28.560 --> 01:22:40.560
And I used to go to the Newport market every Wednesday, take the stock in, you know, in a box to market.

01:22:40.560 --> 01:22:45.560
Then they went to Abergavenny, they closed, they went to Abergavenny and now it's Raglan.

01:22:45.560 --> 01:22:51.560
But it was a... Yes, because they still got a little bit of the old market. They didn't let them take it down, did they?

01:22:51.560 --> 01:22:53.560
Well, as there was, yeah.

01:22:53.560 --> 01:22:54.560
Yeah.

01:22:54.560 --> 01:22:55.560
Yeah.

01:22:55.560 --> 01:22:56.560
But the docks, did you ever go to the docks?

01:22:56.560 --> 01:23:06.560
Yeah. Yes, because we used to love to go to see the docks on a Sunday because you were allowed in there.

01:23:06.560 --> 01:23:07.560
Yes.

01:23:07.560 --> 01:23:14.560
And you pedal your bikes, look, and you go and watch the ships and the big ships and nobody ever saw you.

